<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/F45A4578-F962-4EFA-9CC1-9F2FF4F760AE"><gtr:id>F45A4578-F962-4EFA-9CC1-9F2FF4F760AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>Cranfield University</gtr:name><gtr:department>Sch of Management</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Cranfield</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Bedford</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Bedfordshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>MK43 0AL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/F45A4578-F962-4EFA-9CC1-9F2FF4F760AE"><gtr:id>F45A4578-F962-4EFA-9CC1-9F2FF4F760AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>Cranfield University</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Cranfield</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Bedford</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Bedfordshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>MK43 0AL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/EAA6798C-DF9E-4B2E-82E9-4E01540EE735"><gtr:id>EAA6798C-DF9E-4B2E-82E9-4E01540EE735</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>David</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Denyer</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG037825%2F1"><gtr:id>70E51FB4-73EB-4FAD-AA3E-4E38BC494749</gtr:id><gtr:title>The dark side of management practices: routine non-conformity, non-adoption and adverse events</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G037825/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Fellowship activities explored the factors or conditions that enable or constrain the diffusion, implementation and institutionalisation of management practices following extreme events.&amp;nbsp;Accidents, crises and disasters often hit the headlines but also occur regularly beyond the public gaze. Following an extreme event, organisations often locally fashion new practices, redesign processes and procedures and implement new work methods to prevent or limit recurrence. In many instances a Board of Inquiry also publishes recommendations for change, codifying practices to be implemented not only in the organisations that suffered the extreme event but also throughout the sector. However, the diffusion, adoption and institutionalisation of new practices in this context have proved problematic.&amp;nbsp;Surprisingly, this issue has attracted little attention from management researchers.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Six cross-sector case studies were produced, derived from interviews, local documentation and information in the public domain.&amp;nbsp;The research offers a distinctive managerial perspective on extreme events.&amp;nbsp;This way of thinking offers a foundation for realistic guidance on how change implementation could be improved and the forms of support required for managers to build their capacity as change agents. The findings also have relevance and applicability to our understanding of management practices and managing change in 'normal' or less extreme conditions.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>137682</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The research offers a distinctive managerial perspective, opening a fourth field to help understand extreme events and change, adding to the more traditional approaches offered by political science, engineering and psychology. In addition to macro-level contingencies, micro- level interactions and technologies, organisations can also play an important role in producing extreme events. Management practices that are designed to control interactively complex socio-technical systems can also have emergent, unanticipated and irreducible effects on the reliability of the system often resulting in physical harm or damage to reputation and brand. 



In combination, organisation theory and the empirical analysis suggest that certain structures, processes and mechanisms are generic across extreme events, having ramifications for both theory and management practice. First, all six events proceeded through broadly comparable phases: pre-crisis or incubation period, incident, crisis response management, investigation, organisational learning and implementation of 'lessons learned'. Few previous studies cover the whole event sequence. 



Second, identifying the causes of extreme events and the effects of changes to management practices is problematic. The causality of extreme events usually involves the combination and interaction of numerous factors, at different levels of analysis, over time. Goldstone's concept of 'conjunctural causality' is central to our understanding, identifying the clusters, combinations, or configurations of factors that explain the consequences of interest. 



Third, practices designed to limit adverse events are dynamic not static. Snook's concept of 'practical drift' and Feldmand and Pentland's separation of the ostensive and performative are important in understanding how the actions of actors (the performative) often uncouple over time from the idealized schema that actors form relating to a routine practice (the ostensive) or written procedure.



Fourth, the implementation agenda in aftermath of an extreme event can be described as a wicked problem due to the multiplicity of stakeholders, the socially constructed nature of 'extreme' events, ambiguity relating to the cause, lack of precedents, the opportunity cost and unintended consequences of interventions, the difficulty of learning by trial and error and the inability to define an achievable endpoint - how safe is safe enough? The role of the media often also plays a significant role, shaping public perception and often transforming 'incidents' into 'real crises' worthy of a front-page story. The public inquiry process, by codifying new practices based on past events, may contribute to implementation failures, by stifling the capacity for adaptive and creative responses to deal with idiosyncratic future events. 



Fifth, there are a number of areas where managers in their role as change agents might improve change implementation. These are, the nature and use of recommendations, the surfacing and resolution of underlying systemic issues, the use of parallel management structures to handle different segments of the organisational agenda at different stages in the event timeline, shifting from defensive to progressive agendas, the leadership mind-sets and behaviours exhibited in 'high reliability' and 'resilient' organisations and the reframing of past events as 'praiseworthy failures' thereby turning damaging events into positive opportunities.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Tare a number of areas where managers in their role as change agents might improve change implementation. These are, the nature and use of recommendations, the surfacing and resolution of underlying systemic issues, the use of parallel management structures to handle different segments of the organisational agenda at different stages in the event timeline, shifting from defensive to progressive agendas, the leadership mind-sets and behaviours exhibited in 'high reliability' and 'resilient' organisations and the reframing of past events as 'praiseworthy failures' thereby turning damaging events into positive opportunities.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>E57FAF2E-C1C4-406F-953C-B7942A8C1647</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-6148319594.700187b2f18b84</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Healthcare,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>D8CEF7F5-7EE6-4648-9525-59EA7249B57B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Risk management pervasiveness and organisational maturity: a critical review</gtr:title><gtr:parentPu